H1> User classes explained

P> User classes are e107's permission primitive. Almost every visibility setting on the site (news, links, downloads, menus, individual BBCodes…) is expressed as "available to class X".

Q> What are these user-classes I keep seeing? What are they for?
A> User classes restrict access to certain areas or functions of the site. Define a class, add users to it, and you can scope content so [b]only[/b] members of that class see it.

P> A built-in example is the `PRIVATEFORUM` class: add users to it and create a forum visible only to that class, and the forum becomes invisible to everyone else.

H1> Hierarchy and inheritance

Q> What does the [b]class parent[/b] field do?
A> Since 2.x you can build a class hierarchy: users in a child class automatically inherit the rights of the parent class. Set the parent to [b]Everyone[/b] to opt out of inheritance.

TIP> Use a hierarchy when you have layered membership (e.g. Member → Premium → Lifetime). A premium user automatically has all member privileges without needing to be added to two classes.

H1> Default membership for new users

Q> I want new users to start with membership of certain classes.
A> Open the [b]Userclass[/b] menu and tick the classes you want assigned automatically on signup. You can also choose whether the membership is granted immediately, or only when the account is verified.

WARN> Be careful which classes you mark as "default on signup" – any abusive guest registration will inherit those privileges.
